#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Flight Preparation & Effects of Controls",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 1 | E1/E2",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Flight Preparation & Effects of Controls]

,aim: [
Introduce flight preparation procedures and ground operations. Operate the primary and ancillary controls, observing and understanding their effects on the aircraft.
]

,overview: [
This is the student's first formal lesson. The instructor introduces (but not necessarily in full detail) the student to the pre-flight sequence — documentation, aircraft inspection, and ground handling. Then, the instructor demonstrates all the primary and further effects of all flight controls in the training area. The instructor conducts the takeoff with the student following through on controls. This lesson establishes airmanship principles, correct control technique, and horizon referencing skills that underpin all subsequent training. Non-technical skills are introduced from the outset, with emphasis on IMSAFE, Threat and Error Management (TEM), and correct control handover procedures.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Identify the documents required to be carried on every flight and explain why each is required
- Identify the three axes of movement (longitudinal, lateral, normal) and associated planes (roll, pitch, yaw)
- Recall the primary effect of each primary control (elevator, aileron, rudder)
- Recall the further effects of ailerons and rudder, including spiral tendency
- Explain the effect of trim, power, slipstream, airspeed, and flaps on aircraft control
- Understand the concept of positive, neutral and negative stability

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Taxi the aircraft using power, rudder pedals, and brakes as appropriate
- Apply smooth, positive control inputs to achieve a desired aircraft attitude (±10° roll/pitch)
- Develop understanding of trim and how to relieve control loads
- Interpret basic instrument indications, accounting for parallax errors
- Conduct a pre-flight inspection and aircraft start using the POH checklist

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- Apply IMSAFE self-assessment and confirm fitness to fly before each flight
- Use correct control handover and follow-me-through procedures
- Maintain effective lookout using a systematic scan
- [TEM] Identify see-and-avoid and ground operation hazards as threats; verbalise at least one threat when prompted
- [SA] Monitor ground operations: surrounding aircraft, confined spaces, prop wash, and wind effects
- [HF] Recognise parallax error in instruments and horizon referencing from left seat
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aircraft Attitude/Movements *(Pg 101, 102)*
- The Primary Flying Controls *(Pg 103-105)*
- Further Effects, spiral dive, slipstream and speed *(Pg 103-107)*
- Lift Augmentation and trim *(Pg 126–131)*
- Aerodynamics — The Basics *(Pg 110–118)*
- Human Factors — IMSAFE, TEM, SA *(Pg 3, 13–16, 45)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 40 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft model, access to slideshow \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [TEM] See-and-avoid and threats during ground operations (prop blast, wind, other aircraft)
- [CRM] Control handover: "I have control / you have control" and "follow me through" procedure
- [HF] Parallax error — instrument and horizon referencing
- [HF] IMSAFE: introduced and discussed
- [SA] Airport layout, runup area, confined spaces, wind awareness

*Axes and Planes of Movement* (5 minutes)
- Longitudinal, lateral, and normal axes. Roll, pitch, and yaw

*Stability* (5 minutes)
- Positive, neutral, and negative stability. Brief in-flight demonstration planned

*Primary Controls* (10 minutes)
- Primary effects: elevator — pitch, ailerons — roll, rudder — yaw
- Secondary and further effects.
- #underline[Emphasis: elevator is the primary airspeed control]

*Ancillary Controls* (10 minutes)
- Trim: removes aerodynamic force, does not change attitude
- Power and slipstream: pitch up/down and yaw with power changes
- Airspeed: effect on control feel and effectiveness
- Flaps: lift, drag, and pitch change with extension and retraction

*Ground Operations* (5 minutes)
- Pre-flight inspection overview; checklist use; fuel check; documentation folder
- Safe taxiing: runup area, airport layout, wind corrections, prop wash considerations
- Required documents are confirmed during the pre-flight inspection; if any are missing, the flight does not proceed
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Review weather, NOTAMs, and maintenance release separately from student
- Introduce IMSAFE and confirm student fitness to fly
- Conduct pre-flight inspection with student, emphasising control surfaces, fuel drains, and documentation (show folder only)
- Introduce checklist - explain purpose and discipline of checklist use
- Demonstrate parallax error using instruments on ground
- Brief safe taxiing procedure, runup area layout, wind correction inputs and parallax error

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment verbally and confirm fitness to fly
- Follow instructor through pre-flight inspection, identifying items checked
- Complete startup checklist with instructor guidance
- Taxi aircraft under close instructor guidance — power, rudder pedals, brakes
- Practice wind correction control positions while stationary and while taxiing
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*E8 Takeoff Progression — Lesson 1*]
Instructor conducts takeoff. Student follows through on controls throughout the ground roll, liftoff, and initial climb. No control responsibility transferred during takeoff.

#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Stability: brief demonstration of positive pitch stability during transit to training area
- Parallax: brief demonstration of horizon referencing difference between left and right seat
- Primary effects, one control at a time: elevator (±10° pitch), ailerons (±30° roll), rudder (±10° yaw)
- Further effects: airspeed/RPM from elevator; slip, yaw and spiral tendency from aileron; skid, roll and spiral tendency from rudder
- Power: pitch up/down, yaw and roll tendency
- Flaps: pitch change with extension and retraction, power change requirement due to drag
- Effect of airspeed on control feel: high vs low speed control response
- Trim: demonstrate hands-off stability after trimming correctly
- Upset limits: demonstrate safe attitude limits in pitch

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Elevator inputs: pitch to ±10°, observe airspeed change and RPM follows
- Aileron inputs: roll to ±30°, observe effects, return to straight and level
- Rudder inputs: yaw to ±10°, observe effects, return to straight and level
- Power changes: set full power and idle, observe pitch and yaw effects
- Trim: operate elevator up and down trim, feel control forces, use to relieve forces
- Flaps: operate flaps within limits, observe pitch and drag change
- Use the _further effects_ of the controls to change the aircraft attitude.
- Lookout: practice systematic scan (horizon, left, front, right, above and below)
]

,common_errors:[
- *Overcontrolling*: Encourage smooth inputs — two fingers on stick.
- *Poor lookout*: Prompt systematic scan with a specific pattern and timing.
- *Fixating on instruments*: Horizon is the primary reference — instruments confirm, not set.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes what went well and what was challenging (e.g. "I kept overcontrolling with the ailerons" or "I wasn't sure which way to trim").
- *Instructor Feedback* (5 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (P, S, C, or NC).
  - Highlight strengths (e.g. good lookout awareness) and areas for improvement (e.g. trim direction).
  - Discuss TEM/SA: "You noticed the other traffic — good SA."
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "What did changing the power settings do to our altitude?"
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. Begin Bob Tait reading as below.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing — may advance to Lesson 2*]
- *Control inputs*: Overcontrolling present but reducing; no persistent opposite or dangerous inputs
- *Lookout*: Maintains a lookout scan with regular prompting
- *Theory*: Names primary controls and their primary effects with minor prompting
- *Ground operations*: Completes startup checklist with guidance; taxis with instructor control assistance
- *Airmanship*: Completes IMSAFE with prompting; verbalises at least one TEM threat when prompted

#text(size:12pt)[*Solo Standard (S) — required before first solo*]
- *Control inputs*: Beginning to apply smooth inputs without gross overcontrolling (NC if persistent jerky or opposite inputs)
- *Lookout*: Beginning to maintain a lookout scan without constant prompting
- *Theory*: Can name primary controls and their primary effects with some prompting
- *Ground operations*: Completes startup checklist with guidance; taxis at appropriate speed with basic wind awareness
- *Airmanship*: Completes IMSAFE verbally; verbalises at least one TEM threat when prompted
- *Outcome*: Recorded in student records (P, S, C, or NC) with comments for improvement.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Horizon clearly visible, ceiling \>2000 ft, surface wind \<25 knots
- *Altitude*: Conduct manoeuvres above 1500 ft AGL
- *Emergency Procedures*: Instructor pre-selects forced landing area before conducting airwork
- *TEM*:
  - Instructor retains authority — student following through or practicing with close supervision throughout
  - Monitor for student anxiety or disorientation; pause, assess and continue or cut lesson short if needed
  - Monitor traffic throughout training area operations
  - Maintain SA regarding controlled airspace
- *Aircraft Limits*: Avoid exceeding Vno; demonstrate control effects gently — no abrupt inputs.
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Controls: Pages 101-107 (aircraft attitude, primary controls, further effects, slipstream, trim)
  - Aerodynamics: Pages 110-113 (aerofoils, lift, control surface effects)
  - Human Factors: Pages 3, 13–16, 45 (IMSAFE, TEM, situational awareness)
- Reflect on lesson: "How would gusty conditions change the way you use the controls? What extra corrections might you need to make?"
]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)